docs.abstract: Volunteers have provided first aid at protests since at least the 1960s. Many of them owe their training to Ann Hirschman.
docs.snippet: Volunteers have provided first aid at protests since at least the 1960s. Many of them owe their training to Ann Hirschman.
docs.lead_paragraph: As protests against police brutality have swept the country, in some cases leading to additional police aggression, toward demonstrators, a loosely organized group of trained volunteers has been on call to intervene and treat injuries.

headline.print_headline: The Very Model of a Street-Healing Woman

docs.abstract: From Virginia to New Mexico, protests over police brutality have brought hundreds of years of American history bubbling to the surface.
docs.snippet: From Virginia to New Mexico, protests over police brutality have brought hundreds of years of American history bubbling to the surface.
docs.lead_paragraph: The boiling anger that exploded in the days after George Floyd gasped his final breaths is now fueling a national movement to topple perceived symbols of racism and oppression in the United States, as protests over police brutality against African-Americans expand to include demands for a more honest accounting of American history.

headline.main: Reconsidering the Past, One Statue at a Time
headline.print_headline: Reconsidering the Past, One Statue at a Time

byline.original: By Sarah Mervosh, Simon Romero and Lucy Tompkins

docs.abstract: The delay drew some criticism from players. But one professor noted the league’s off-field actions provided crucial context for any public statement.
docs.snippet: The delay drew some criticism from players. But one professor noted the league’s off-field actions provided crucial context for any public statement.
docs.lead_paragraph: Five days after George Floyd was killed while in custody of the Minneapolis police on May 25, N.F.L. Commissioner Roger Goodell released a 150-word statement about the death and ensuing protests. The N.H.L. and N.B.A. followed suit the next day.

headline.main: M.L.B. Took 9 Days to Address George Floyd. Was It Too Late?
headline.print_headline: A League’s First Comment, at Last

docs.abstract: Flanked by the family of Mr. Floyd, the Rev. Al Sharpton said, “It’s time to stand up and say, ‘Get your knee off our necks.’”
docs.snippet: Flanked by the family of Mr. Floyd, the Rev. Al Sharpton said, “It’s time to stand up and say, ‘Get your knee off our necks.’”
docs.lead_paragraph: MINNEAPOLIS — Hundreds of people filed into a Minneapolis chapel on Thursday to remember George Floyd, the man whose death at the hands of the police opened a nationwide flood of anguish, protest and demands for change in American policing.

headline.main: At George Floyd Memorial, an Anguished Call for Change
headline.print_headline: At Floyd Service, A Cry of Pain: ‘Get Your Knee Off Our Necks’

docs.abstract: Rather than tear down statues, some argue that the past should not be obliterated, but remembered and explained.
docs.snippet: Rather than tear down statues, some argue that the past should not be obliterated, but remembered and explained.
docs.lead_paragraph: BORDEAUX, France — At a bend in the river, a succession of stately stone buildings, each more imposing than the last, stretches along the left bank. Their elegant 18th-century facades had helped Bordeaux, already famous for its wineries, become a UNESCO World Heritage site.

headline.main: George Floyd’s Killing Forces Wider Debate on France’s Slave-Trading Past
headline.print_headline: Floyd’s Death Forces a Deeper Debate on France’s Slave-Trading Past

docs.abstract: High school students have organized protests in California, Maryland and Michigan. In one Texas suburb, three teenagers led hundreds of people in a march, and they say they aren’t done organizing.
docs.snippet: High school students have organized protests in California, Maryland and Michigan. In one Texas suburb, three teenagers led hundreds of people in a march, and they say they aren’t done organizing.
docs.lead_paragraph: In early June, as outrage over racism and police brutality erupted nationwide, three teenagers from Katy, Texas, grew frustrated by a void of activism in their affluent Houston suburb.

headline.main: ‘I Need People to Hear My Voice’: Teens Protest Racism

docs.abstract: One white counterprotester yelled while kneeling on the neck of another who was facedown on the ground. The display drew fierce condemnation.
docs.snippet: One white counterprotester yelled while kneeling on the neck of another who was facedown on the ground. The display drew fierce condemnation.
docs.lead_paragraph: The protest in the southern New Jersey township was similar to those that have unfolded across the United States since George Floyd was killed in police custody: About 70 people gathered to rally against police brutality and systemic racism.

headline.main: Man Who Mocked George Floyd’s Killing Is Fired by FedEx

byline.original: By Ed Shanahan and Tracey Tully

docs.abstract: Joe Biden appears in a stronger position to oust an incumbent president than any challenger since Bill Clinton in the summer of 1992.
docs.snippet: Joe Biden appears in a stronger position to oust an incumbent president than any challenger since Bill Clinton in the summer of 1992.
docs.lead_paragraph: The coronavirus pandemic, a severe economic downturn and the widespread demonstrations in the aftermath of the death of George Floyd in police custody would pose a serious political challenge to any president seeking re-election. They are certainly posing one to President Trump.

headline.main: Wave of New Polling Suggests an Erosion of Trump’s Support
headline.print_headline: New Numbers Suggest a Major Erosion of Trump’s Support

docs.abstract: Some came to the streets to dance. Others were moved to dance more spontaneously, and surprised to find themselves seen by millions online.
docs.snippet: Some came to the streets to dance. Others were moved to dance more spontaneously, and surprised to find themselves seen by millions online.
docs.lead_paragraph: As protesters streamed through the streets of New York on Sunday afternoon, one group’s chants of “Black lives matter!” and “No justice, no peace!” gave way to a sound more often heard at weddings and block parties. On 125th Street in Harlem, hundreds of people, many of them professional dancers, had congregated for a peaceful march across town and a collective performance of the Electric Slide.

headline.main: Dancing Bodies That Proclaim: Black Lives Matter

docs.abstract: Eight correctional officers said people of color who work in the jail were initially moved away from Derek Chauvin, the officer accused of killing George Floyd.
docs.snippet: Eight correctional officers said people of color who work in the jail were initially moved away from Derek Chauvin, the officer accused of killing George Floyd.
docs.lead_paragraph: ST. PAUL, Minn. — Staff members working at the jail that held Derek Chauvin, the white officer charged with murder in the killing of George Floyd, say that only white employees were allowed to guard him when he was first brought to the facility last month.

headline.main: Jail Only Allowed White Staff to Guard Ex-Officer Charged With Killing George Floyd
headline.print_headline: Jail Had White Staff Guard Ex-Officer Held in Floyd Case
